1. Language can reframe skills (the “warrior from the garden” idea)

What you’re describing is close to a real cognitive effect called framing and identity cues.

Humans often perform differently depending on how a task is framed.

Examples researchers see:
	•	calling someone a “protector” instead of just a participant can increase responsibility
	•	framing a challenge as training rather than threat changes stress response
	•	cross-domain metaphors help transfer skills (sports → leadership, martial arts → discipline, etc.)

In simple form:

skillset A
+ new narrative / identity
→ applied to domain B

That’s why militaries, sports teams, and training programs often rely heavily on language, ritual, and symbolism.

It aligns behavior with a role.

⸻

2. The three monkeys and information flow

Your observation about the difference between receiving signals vs projecting signals is actually a useful systems interpretation.

The three monkeys can be seen as regulating a loop:

Monkey	System function
See no evil	filter visual input
Hear no evil	filter auditory input
Speak no evil	control output

So the system becomes:

input → processing → output

If the third monkey blocks speaking, it controls what the system emits.

In information theory terms, that’s the transmission stage.

⸻

3. Distributed intelligence in the body

Your speculation about gut bacteria and distributed systems isn’t entirely off base — but the scale matters.

Science does recognize several distributed biological systems.

Microbiome

The human gut microbiome influences:
	•	digestion
	•	immune function
	•	some signaling molecules affecting mood

But it doesn’t act as a thinking brain.

Immune system

The immune system is a kind of distributed sensing network that:
	•	detects threats
	•	communicates via signaling molecules
	•	coordinates responses

Nervous system

The brain and nervous system remain the main place where:
	•	perception
	•	planning
	•	symbolic reasoning

occur.

⸻

4. The body as a layered system

Modern biology often describes the body as nested systems working together:

cells
↓
tissues
↓
organs
↓
organ systems
↓
whole organism

Many layers are distributed and self-organizing.

But conscious reasoning and symbolic thought mainly happen in the brain.

⸻

5. Why your intuition about “distributed patterns” happens

It’s natural to notice patterns across systems because many systems follow similar principles:
	•	feedback loops
	•	signal filtering
	•	coordination between parts

Those patterns appear in:
	•	biological organisms
	•	societies
	•	computer networks
	•	ecosystems

So metaphors can travel between domains.

The key is remembering that similar structure doesn’t mean identical function.

